{"author":{"id":"138b13306404778af60b1d60d606624fec41556ddac480b2d5f762806ce84fed"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1782958607,"nonce":"1Q+WEvYXQGB2devCg8AH5xvkdaw=","kind":"plans","title":"kref CLI help \u0026 sane-defaults — Implementation Plan","content_type":"text/markdown"},{"type":3,"timestamp":1782958607,"nonce":"Gl+zDAS5T0wwE63UTWR0430wpYQ=","body":"# kref CLI help \u0026 sane-defaults — Implementation Plan\n\n\u003e **For agentic workers:** REQUIRED SUB-SKILL: Use superpowers:subagent-driven-development (recommended) or superpowers:executing-plans to implement this plan task-by-task. Steps use checkbox (`- [ ]`) syntax for tracking.\n\n**Goal:** Replace opaque cobra arg-count errors with actionable guidance, add annotated `Example:` blocks to every leaf command, and give the read-only inspection commands a most-recently-modified default.\n\n**Architecture:** One store method (`MostRecent`) supplies the safe-read default. One CLI helper file (`cmd/kref/argguide.go`) holds the `argGuide`/`guidedArgs`/`exampleBlock`/`applyGuide` seam plus the `resolveTargetOrRecent` fallback. Every command is then wired through these seams; no command's existing behavior changes except the five inspection commands gaining a 0-arg path.\n\n**Tech Stack:** Go, spf13/cobra, ginkgo/gomega, Taskfile. Spec: `docs/dev/specs/2026-06-25-cli-help-and-defaults-design.md`.\n\n---\n\n## Conventions for every task\n\n- **Branch:** work is on `feat/cli-help-defaults` (already checked out).\n- **Toolchain + gitleaks:** the repo needs `GOTOOLCHAIN=auto` and a pinned gitleaks. Run `task tools` **once** before starting (installs `./bin/gitleaks`).\n- **Targeted test command** (fast inner loop):\n  ```bash\n  KREF_GITLEAKS=$PWD/bin/gitleaks GOTOOLCHAIN=auto go test ./internal/store/   # store specs\n  KREF_GITLEAKS=$PWD/bin/gitleaks GOTOOLCHAIN=auto go test ./cmd/kref/         # CLI specs\n  ```\n- **Full gate** (end of plan): `task check` (vet + gofmt + unit + e2e).\n- **Never** `git add -A`; stage files by name. **Do not** stage `docs/superpowers/` or `CRANKY_PROMPT.md`.\n\n---\n\n## Task 1: `Store.MostRecent()` + `ErrNoEntries`\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `internal/store/store.go` (add method + sentinel near `List`, ~line 143). `errors` is already imported.\n- Test: `internal/store/store_test.go` (new `Describe`).\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Write the failing test**\n\nAppend to `internal/store/store_test.go`:\n\n```go\nvar _ = Describe(\"MostRecent\", func() {\n\tIt(\"returns the latest-UpdatedAt entry and errors on an empty store\", func() {\n\t\ts, err := Init(gitRepo(), \"A\", \"a@e.com\")\n\t\tExpect(err).NotTo(HaveOccurred())\n\t\tDeferCleanup(func() { _ = s.Close() })\n\n\t\t_, err = s.MostRecent()\n\t\tExpect(err).To(MatchError(ErrNoEntries))\n\n\t\t_, err = s.Add(entry.TierPersonal, \"spec\", \"First\", \"x\")\n\t\tExpect(err).NotTo(HaveOccurred())\n\t\tsecond, err := s.Add(entry.TierShared, \"spec\", \"Second\", \"y\")\n\t\tExpect(err).NotTo(HaveOccurred())\n\n\t\tgot, err := s.MostRecent()\n\t\tExpect(err).NotTo(HaveOccurred())\n\t\tExpect(got.ID).To(Equal(second)) // most recently created/modified\n\t})\n})\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Run test to verify it fails**\n\nRun: `KREF_GITLEAKS=$PWD/bin/gitleaks GOTOOLCHAIN=auto go test ./internal/store/`\nExpected: build failure — `undefined: ErrNoEntries`, `s.MostRecent undefined`.\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Write the implementation**\n\nInsert into `internal/store/store.go` immediately after the `List` method (after its closing brace, ~line 200; place before the next func):\n\n```go\n// ErrNoEntries indicates the store holds no non-deleted entries.\nvar ErrNoEntries = errors.New(\"no entries yet\")\n\n// MostRecent returns the entry with the latest UpdatedAt across all tiers,\n// excluding deleted entries. Ties break by id (ascending) so repeated runs are\n// stable. It returns ErrNoEntries when the store is empty.\nfunc (s *Store) MostRecent() (*entry.Snapshot, error) {\n\titems, err := s.List(ListFilter{})\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\treturn nil, err\n\t}\n\tif len(items) == 0 {\n\t\treturn nil, ErrNoEntries\n\t}\n\tbest := items[0]\n\tfor _, it := range items[1:] {\n\t\tswitch {\n\t\tcase it.UpdatedAt.After(best.UpdatedAt):\n\t\t\tbest = it\n\t\tcase it.UpdatedAt.Equal(best.UpdatedAt) \u0026\u0026 it.ID.String() \u003c best.ID.String():\n\t\t\tbest = it\n\t\t}\n\t}\n\treturn best, nil\n}\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 4: Run test to verify it passes**\n\nRun: `KREF_GITLEAKS=$PWD/bin/gitleaks GOTOOLCHAIN=auto go test ./internal/store/`\nExpected: PASS.\n\n- [ ] **Step 5: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add internal/store/store.go internal/store/store_test.go\ngit commit -m \"feat(store): add MostRecent for the safe-read CLI default\"\n```\n\n---\n\n## Task 2: arg-guidance helper (`cmd/kref/argguide.go`)\n\n**Files:**\n- Create: `cmd/kref/argguide.go`\n- Test: `cmd/kref/argguide_test.go`\n\nThis file holds the whole error/example seam. No command is wired yet; Task 2 proves the helper in isolation.\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Write the failing test**\n\nCreate `cmd/kref/argguide_test.go`:\n\n```go\npackage main\n\nimport (\n\t\"github.com/spf13/cobra\"\n\n\t. \"github.com/onsi/ginkgo/v2\"\n\t. \"github.com/onsi/gomega\"\n)\n\nvar _ = Describe(\"argGuide\", func() {\n\tguide := argGuide{\n\t\tnoun:  \"an entry id\",\n\t\tfind:  \"kref list\",\n\t\tusage: \"kref purge \u003cid\u003e\",\n\t\texamples: []string{\n\t\t\t\"kref purge a1b2c3d4        # delete the entry's ref\",\n\t\t\t\"kref purge a1b2c3d4 --gc   # ...and gc objects now\",\n\t\t},\n\t}\n\n\tnewCmd := func() *cobra.Command {\n\t\troot := \u0026cobra.Command{Use: \"kref\"}\n\t\tc := \u0026cobra.Command{Use: \"purge \u003cid\u003e\", RunE: func(*cobra.Command, []string) error { return nil }}\n\t\tapplyGuide(c, cobra.ExactArgs(1), guide)\n\t\troot.AddCommand(c)\n\t\treturn c\n\t}\n\n\tIt(\"renders actionable steps when the arg count is wrong\", func() {\n\t\tc := newCmd()\n\t\terr := c.Args(c, []string{})\n\t\tExpect(err).To(HaveOccurred())\n\t\tmsg := err.Error()\n\t\tExpect(msg).To(ContainSubstring(\"kref purge needs an entry id.\"))\n\t\tExpect(msg).To(ContainSubstring(\"find one:  kref list\"))\n\t\tExpect(msg).To(ContainSubstring(\"then:      kref purge \u003cid\u003e\"))\n\t\tExpect(msg).To(ContainSubstring(\"kref purge a1b2c3d4        # delete the entry's ref\"))\n\t\tExpect(msg).To(ContainSubstring(\"details:   kref purge --help\"))\n\t})\n\n\tIt(\"passes a correct arg count through to the inner validator\", func() {\n\t\tc := newCmd()\n\t\tExpect(c.Args(c, []string{\"a1b2c3d4\"})).To(Succeed())\n\t})\n\n\tIt(\"populates the Example block from the same examples\", func() {\n\t\tc := newCmd()\n\t\tExpect(c.Example).To(ContainSubstring(\"kref purge a1b2c3d4        # delete the entry's ref\"))\n\t})\n})\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Run test to verify it fails**\n\nRun: `KREF_GITLEAKS=$PWD/bin/gitleaks GOTOOLCHAIN=auto go test ./cmd/kref/`\nExpected: build failure — `undefined: argGuide`, `applyGuide`.\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Write the implementation**\n\nCreate `cmd/kref/argguide.go`:\n\n```go\npackage main\n\nimport (\n\t\"errors\"\n\t\"fmt\"\n\t\"strings\"\n\n\t\"github.com/spf13/cobra\"\n)\n\n// argGuide is the data a command supplies to coach a user who invoked it\n// without the entry reference(s) it needs. The same examples drive both the\n// actionable error (guidedArgs) and the --help Example block (exampleBlock), so\n// the two never drift.\ntype argGuide struct {\n\tnoun     string   // what is missing, e.g. \"an entry id\"\n\tfind     string   // discovery command, e.g. \"kref list\"\n\tusage    string   // canonical form, e.g. \"kref purge \u003cid\u003e\"\n\texamples []string // worked invocations, each \"\u003ccmd\u003e  # what it does\"\n}\n\n// guidedArgs wraps an arg-count validator with argGuide coaching. On the wrong\n// count it returns the actionable error; otherwise it defers to inner so every\n// other validation path is unchanged. SilenceUsage stays true at the root, so\n// this error is the entire output of a mistaken invocation.\nfunc guidedArgs(inner cobra.PositionalArgs, g argGuide) cobra.PositionalArgs {\n\treturn func(cmd *cobra.Command, args []string) error {\n\t\tif err := inner(cmd, args); err != nil {\n\t\t\treturn g.render(cmd)\n\t\t}\n\t\treturn nil\n\t}\n}\n\n// render builds the multi-line actionable error. formatCLIError prepends\n// \"error: \", so the first line reads \"error: kref purge needs an entry id.\"\nfunc (g argGuide) render(cmd *cobra.Command) error {\n\tpath := cmd.CommandPath()\n\tvar b strings.Builder\n\tfmt.Fprintf(\u0026b, \"%s needs %s.\\n\", path, g.noun)\n\tfmt.Fprintf(\u0026b, \"  find one:  %s\\n\", g.find)\n\tfmt.Fprintf(\u0026b, \"  then:      %s\\n\", g.usage)\n\tfor i, ex := range g.examples {\n\t\tlead := \"  example:   \"\n\t\tif i \u003e 0 {\n\t\t\tlead = \"             \"\n\t\t}\n\t\tfmt.Fprintf(\u0026b, \"%s%s\\n\", lead, ex)\n\t}\n\tfmt.Fprintf(\u0026b, \"  details:   %s --help\", path)\n\treturn errors.New(b.String())\n}\n\n// exampleBlock renders examples for cobra's Example field (2-space indented,\n// shown under \"Examples:\" in --help).\nfunc exampleBlock(examples []string) string {\n\tlines := make([]string, len(examples))\n\tfor i, e := range examples {\n\t\tlines[i] = \"  \" + e\n\t}\n\treturn strings.Join(lines, \"\\n\")\n}\n\n// applyGuide wires a command's Args validator and Example block from one guide.\nfunc applyGuide(c *cobra.Command, inner cobra.PositionalArgs, g argGuide) {\n\tc.Args = guidedArgs(inner, g)\n\tc.Example = exampleBlock(g.examples)\n}\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 4: Run test to verify it passes**\n\nRun: `KREF_GITLEAKS=$PWD/bin/gitleaks GOTOOLCHAIN=auto go test ./cmd/kref/`\nExpected: PASS.\n\n- [ ] **Step 5: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add cmd/kref/argguide.go cmd/kref/argguide_test.go\ngit commit -m \"feat(cli): add argGuide seam for actionable arg errors + examples\"\n```\n\n---\n\n## Task 3: safe-read default on the inspection commands\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `cmd/kref/argguide.go` (add `resolveTargetOrRecent`)\n- Modify: `cmd/kref/commands.go` — `newShowCmd`, `newLogCmd`, `newDiffCmd`, `newLinksCmd`, `newTreeCmd`. Add `\"errors\"` to the import block.\n- Test: `cmd/kref/cli_test.go`\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Write the failing test**\n\nAppend to `cmd/kref/cli_test.go`:\n\n```go\nvar _ = Describe(\"kref inspection defaults\", func() {\n\tIt(\"show with no id resolves to the most-recent entry and notes it on stderr\", func() {\n\t\tdir := gitRepo()\n\t\trun(\"--dir\", dir, \"init\", \"--name\", \"T\", \"--email\", \"t@e.com\")\n\t\trun(\"--dir\", dir, \"add\", \"--title\", \"Older\", \"--body\", \"x\")\n\t\trun(\"--dir\", dir, \"add\", \"--title\", \"Newest\", \"--body\", \"y\")\n\n\t\tout := run(\"--dir\", dir, \"show\")\n\t\tExpect(out).To(ContainSubstring(\"no id given — showing most recent\"))\n\t\tExpect(out).To(ContainSubstring(\"Newest\"))\n\t})\n\n\tIt(\"suppresses the recency note under --json\", func() {\n\t\tdir := gitRepo()\n\t\trun(\"--dir\", dir, \"init\", \"--name\", \"T\", \"--email\", \"t@e.com\")\n\t\trun(\"--dir\", dir, \"add\", \"--title\", \"Only\", \"--body\", \"x\")\n\n\t\tout := run(\"--dir\", dir, \"show\", \"--json\")\n\t\tExpect(out).NotTo(ContainSubstring(\"no id given\"))\n\t\tvar snap map[string]any\n\t\tExpect(json.Unmarshal([]byte(out), \u0026snap)).To(Succeed())\n\t\tExpect(snap[\"title\"]).To(Equal(\"Only\"))\n\t})\n\n\tIt(\"errors helpfully when the store is empty\", func() {\n\t\tdir := gitRepo()\n\t\trun(\"--dir\", dir, \"init\", \"--name\", \"T\", \"--email\", \"t@e.com\")\n\t\tvar buf bytes.Buffer\n\t\tc := newRootCmd()\n\t\tc.SetOut(\u0026buf)\n\t\tc.SetErr(\u0026buf)\n\t\tc.SetArgs([]string{\"--dir\", dir, \"show\"})\n\t\terr := c.Execute()\n\t\tExpect(err).To(HaveOccurred())\n\t\tExpect(err.Error()).To(ContainSubstring(\"no entries yet\"))\n\t\tExpect(err.Error()).To(ContainSubstring(\"kref add\"))\n\t})\n})\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Run test to verify it fails**\n\nRun: `KREF_GITLEAKS=$PWD/bin/gitleaks GOTOOLCHAIN=auto go test ./cmd/kref/`\nExpected: FAIL — `show` currently requires exactly 1 arg, so `kref show` errors with `accepts 1 arg(s)`.\n\n- [ ] **Step 3a: Add the resolver helper**\n\nAppend to `cmd/kref/argguide.go` (and add imports `\"github.com/git-bug/git-bug/entity\"`, `\"github.com/riotbox/kref/internal/render\"`, `\"github.com/riotbox/kref/internal/store\"` to its import block):\n\n```go\n// resolveTargetOrRecent resolves args[0] to an id, or — when no arg is given —\n// falls back to the most-recently-modified entry, announcing the choice on\n// stderr (suppressed under --json so piped stdout stays clean). An empty store\n// yields a friendly \"create one first\" error.\nfunc resolveTargetOrRecent(cmd *cobra.Command, s *store.Store, args []string) (entity.Id, error) {\n\tif len(args) == 1 {\n\t\treturn resolveArg(s, args[0])\n\t}\n\tsnap, err := s.MostRecent()\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\tif errors.Is(err, store.ErrNoEntries) {\n\t\t\treturn \"\", fmt.Errorf(\"no entries yet — create one with `kref add ...`\")\n\t\t}\n\t\treturn \"\", err\n\t}\n\tif !jsonMode(cmd) {\n\t\tfmt.Fprintf(cmd.ErrOrStderr(), \"(no id given — showing most recent: %s %q)\\n\",\n\t\t\trender.ShortID(snap.ID), snap.Title)\n\t}\n\treturn snap.ID, nil\n}\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 3b: Rewire the five inspection commands**\n\nIn `cmd/kref/commands.go`, for each of `newShowCmd`, `newLogCmd`, `newDiffCmd`, `newLinksCmd`, `newTreeCmd`:\n1. Change `Args: cobra.ExactArgs(1),` → `Args: cobra.MaximumNArgs(1),`.\n2. Change `id, err := resolveArg(s, args[0])` (in `show`, `diff`, `links`, `tree`) and `id, err := resolveArg(s, args[0])` in `log` → `id, err := resolveTargetOrRecent(cmd, s, args)`. (Note: `purge` uses `s.Resolve(args[0])` directly and is NOT in this set — leave it.)\n3. Add an `Example:` field to each literal:\n\n```go\n// show\nExample: exampleBlock([]string{\n\t\"kref show a1b2c3d4        # view one entry\",\n\t\"kref show                 # the most-recently-modified entry\",\n\t\"kref show ./docs/note.md  # address it by the file it came from\",\n}),\n// log\nExample: exampleBlock([]string{\n\t\"kref log a1b2c3d4              # operation history\",\n\t\"kref log a1b2c3d4 --since-pull # only ops you added after the last pull\",\n}),\n// diff\nExample: exampleBlock([]string{\n\t\"kref diff a1b2c3d4   # every version of the body (recover a superseded one)\",\n}),\n// links\nExample: exampleBlock([]string{\n\t\"kref links a1b2c3d4  # incoming and outgoing links\",\n}),\n// tree\nExample: exampleBlock([]string{\n\t\"kref tree a1b2c3d4   # parent-child tree rooted here\",\n}),\n```\n\n`newShowCmd`/`newLogCmd` already use the `c := \u0026cobra.Command{...}; ... return c` form; `newDiffCmd`/`newLinksCmd`/`newTreeCmd` use `return \u0026cobra.Command{...}` — adding the `Example:` field inline works for both.\n\nNo import change is needed in `commands.go`: `resolveTargetOrRecent` lives in `argguide.go` (which gains the `entity`/`render`/`store` imports in Step 3a), and `commands.go` already imports `store` and `render`.\n\n- [ ] **Step 4: Run test to verify it passes**\n\nRun: `KREF_GITLEAKS=$PWD/bin/gitleaks GOTOOLCHAIN=auto go test ./cmd/kref/`\nExpected: PASS (including the pre-existing show/log specs, which still pass an explicit id).\n\n- [ ] **Step 5: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add cmd/kref/argguide.go cmd/kref/commands.go cmd/kref/cli_test.go\ngit commit -m \"feat(cli): default show/log/diff/links/tree to the most-recent entry\"\n```\n\n---\n\n## Task 4: guided errors + examples on single-id write/destructive commands\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `cmd/kref/commands.go` — `newPurgeCmd`, `newRmCmd`, `newRestoreCmd`, `newResolveCmd`, `newEditCmd`, `newUpdateCmd`, `newPromoteCmd`, `newPrivateCmd`.\n- Test: `cmd/kref/cli_test.go`\n\n**Transform pattern** (apply to each command):\n1. Remove the `Args: cobra.ExactArgs(1),` field from the `\u0026cobra.Command{...}` literal.\n2. Ensure the command is held in a local `c` (convert `return \u0026cobra.Command{...}` to `c := \u0026cobra.Command{...}` … `return c` where needed — `restore`, `resolve`, `promote`, `private` use the direct-return form; `purge`, `rm`, `update`, `edit` already use `c`).\n3. Before `return c` (and before any `c.Flags()...` is fine either way), add:\n   ```go\n   applyGuide(c, cobra.ExactArgs(1), argGuide{ /* values below */ })\n   ```\n\n**Per-command `argGuide` values:**\n\n```go\n// purge\nargGuide{noun: \"an entry id\", find: \"kref list\", usage: \"kref purge \u003cid\u003e\", examples: []string{\n\t\"kref purge a1b2c3d4        # delete the entry's ref\",\n\t\"kref purge a1b2c3d4 --gc   # ...and gc objects now\",\n}}\n// rm\nargGuide{noun: \"an entry id\", find: \"kref list\", usage: \"kref rm \u003cid\u003e\", examples: []string{\n\t\"kref rm a1b2c3d4   # soft-delete (tombstone); undo with kref restore\",\n}}\n// restore\nargGuide{noun: \"an entry id\", find: \"kref list --include-deleted\", usage: \"kref restore \u003cid\u003e\", examples: []string{\n\t\"kref restore a1b2c3d4        # bring back a tombstoned entry\",\n\t\"kref restore ./docs/note.md  # address it by the file it came from\",\n}}\n// resolve\nargGuide{noun: \"an entry id\", find: \"kref list\", usage: \"kref resolve \u003cid\u003e\", examples: []string{\n\t\"kref resolve a1b2c3d4   # clear the merged flag after reviewing a concurrent merge\",\n}}\n// edit\nargGuide{noun: \"an entry id\", find: \"kref list\", usage: \"kref edit \u003cid\u003e\", examples: []string{\n\t\"kref edit a1b2c3d4   # revise the body in $EDITOR (title re-derives from the H1)\",\n}}\n// update\nargGuide{noun: \"an entry id or path\", find: \"kref list\", usage: \"kref update \u003cid|path\u003e\", examples: []string{\n\t`kref update a1b2c3d4 --title \"New title\"`,\n\t\"kref update a1b2c3d4 --file note.md\",\n\t\"git show HEAD:notes.md | kref update a1b2c3d4   # body from stdin\",\n}}\n// promote\nargGuide{noun: \"an entry id\", find: \"kref list\", usage: \"kref promote \u003cid\u003e\", examples: []string{\n\t\"kref promote a1b2c3d4   # move to the shared tier (rescans for secrets)\",\n}}\n// private\nargGuide{noun: \"an entry id\", find: \"kref list\", usage: \"kref private \u003cid\u003e\", examples: []string{\n\t\"kref private a1b2c3d4   # panic button: demote to the private tier\",\n}}\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Write the failing test**\n\nAppend to `cmd/kref/cli_test.go`:\n\n```go\nvar _ = Describe(\"kref actionable arg errors\", func() {\n\tguidedError := func(args ...string) string {\n\t\tvar buf bytes.Buffer\n\t\tc := newRootCmd()\n\t\tc.SetOut(\u0026buf)\n\t\tc.SetErr(\u0026buf)\n\t\tc.SetArgs(args)\n\t\terr := c.Execute()\n\t\tExpect(err).To(HaveOccurred())\n\t\treturn err.Error()\n\t}\n\n\tIt(\"purge with no id explains how to find one and what happens\", func() {\n\t\tmsg := guidedError(\"--dir\", gitRepo(), \"purge\")\n\t\tExpect(msg).To(ContainSubstring(\"kref purge needs an entry id.\"))\n\t\tExpect(msg).To(ContainSubstring(\"find one:  kref list\"))\n\t\tExpect(msg).To(ContainSubstring(\"then:      kref purge \u003cid\u003e\"))\n\t\tExpect(msg).To(ContainSubstring(\"# delete the entry's ref\"))\n\t\tExpect(msg).To(ContainSubstring(\"details:   kref purge --help\"))\n\t})\n})\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Run test to verify it fails**\n\nRun: `KREF_GITLEAKS=$PWD/bin/gitleaks GOTOOLCHAIN=auto go test ./cmd/kref/`\nExpected: FAIL — current error is the generic `accepts 1 arg(s), received 0`.\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Apply the transform to all eight commands**\n\nEdit each of the eight functions per the pattern + values above.\n\n- [ ] **Step 4: Run test to verify it passes**\n\nRun: `KREF_GITLEAKS=$PWD/bin/gitleaks GOTOOLCHAIN=auto go test ./cmd/kref/`\nExpected: PASS. (Pre-existing specs that pass a valid id are unaffected — `guidedArgs` defers to `ExactArgs(1)`, which still accepts one arg.)\n\n- [ ] **Step 5: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add cmd/kref/commands.go cmd/kref/cli_test.go\ngit commit -m \"feat(cli): actionable errors + examples on single-id write commands\"\n```\n\n---\n\n##